95	\subsection{Setup: Mayer-Vietoris squares}
96	
97	A \emph{Mayer-Vietoris square} for a Grothendieck topology $J$ on a category $C$ is, informally, a pullback square in $C$
98	\[
99	  \begin{tikzcd}
100	    X_1 \ar[r, "f_{1,2}"] \ar[d, "f_{1,3}"'] & X_2 \ar[d, "f_{2,4}"] \\
101	    X_3 \ar[r, "f_{3,4}"'] & X_4
102	  \end{tikzcd}
103	\]
104	that is a $J$-cover (in the sense that the pair $\{f_{2,4}, f_{3,4}\} : X_2 \sqcup X_3 \to X_4$ is a covering family for $J$, and the pullback to $X_1$ is the obvious one). Mathlib's $\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.MayerVietorisSquare}$ (file \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/MayerVietorisSquare.lean}) bundles this datum together with its sheaf-theoretic exactness properties; we use it as a black box.
105	
106	For us, the canonical example is a 2-affine open cover $X_4 = U_2 \cup U_3$ of an open $X_4 \subseteq C.\mathrm{left}.\mathrm{toTopCat}$ on a curve $C$, with $U_1 = U_2 \cap U_3$. After iter-017 + iter-018 + iter-019 land the LES theorem, this specialisation will be the engine of the Path-2 Serre-finiteness argument (`iter-020+`).
107	
108	\subsection{First LES building block: the sum of two restriction maps}
