\begin{remark}[Why \texttt{def} for the functor and \texttt{abbrev} for the presheaf wrapper]
  Mathlib uses $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{def} for $\mathtt{cohomologyPresheafFunctor}$ (it is the substantive bifunctor; reducibility through it is not needed by downstream consumers) and $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{abbrev} for $\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}$ (the per-fiber evaluation $\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,X)$ is the direct API surface and consumers expect Mathlib-style fiber-level reductions; the $\HPrime$ abbrev pattern at L105 follows the same convention). We mirror this exactly: $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{cohomologyPresheafFunctor}$ as $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{def}; $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}$ as $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{abbrev}. Iter-016 plan-agent re-probe verifies that the \lstinline{abbrev} reducibility is what makes Remark~\ref{rem:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf_eval}'s \lstinline{rfl} work; using \lstinline{def} for the abbrev would break the definitional identification with $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X$.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Toward Mayer-Vietoris LES (iter-017+)]
  Mathlib's Mayer-Vietoris LES (file \texttt{MayerVietoris.lean}) for an abelian sheaf $F$ and a Mayer-Vietoris square $S$ uses both
  \begin{itemize}
    \item the carrier $F.\mathtt{H}'\,n\,S.X_i$ (= cohomology-of-an-open) — supplied here on the $\ModuleCat\,k$ side by iter-014 $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X$,
    \item the restriction maps $(F.\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}\,n).\mathrm{map}\,S.f_{ij}.\mathtt{op}$ (= functoriality in $X$) — supplied here on the $\ModuleCat\,k$ side by iter-016 $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}\,k\,F\,n$.
  \end{itemize}
  With both prerequisites in place, the LES theorem on the $\ModuleCat\,k$ side is then a direct line-by-line mirror of Mathlib's \texttt{MayerVietoris.lean}. The iter-016 work is therefore the last algebraic prerequisite before the substantive iter-017+ LES theorem can be stated and proved.
\end{remark}

\section{Mayer-Vietoris LES building blocks: \texorpdfstring{$\toBiprod$}{toBiprod} and \texorpdfstring{$\fromBiprod$}{fromBiprod} (iter-017)}
\label{sec:hmodule_prime_mayer_vietoris_first}

After Definitions~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}--\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf} the cohomology-of-an-open carrier $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X$, its $H^0$ identification, and its contravariant-in-$X$ functoriality (assembled into the presheaf $\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n$) are all in scope. Iter-017 attacks the Mayer-Vietoris long exact sequence on the $\ModuleCat\,k$ side directly, mirroring Mathlib's \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/MayerVietoris.lean} (file authored by J.~Riou) line-by-line for $\Sheaf\,J\,\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves but with $F.\cohomologyPresheaf$ replaced by $\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F$. The first two LES building blocks are the sum and difference of two restriction maps; both are one-line term-mode \texttt{biprod.lift} / \texttt{biprod.desc} bodies, probe-confirmed by the iter-017 plan-agent.

\subsection{Setup: Mayer-Vietoris squares}

A \emph{Mayer-Vietoris square} for a Grothendieck topology $J$ on a category $C$ is, informally, a pullback square in $C$
\[
  \begin{tikzcd}
    X_1 \ar[r, "f_{1,2}"] \ar[d, "f_{1,3}"'] & X_2 \ar[d, "f_{2,4}"] \\
    X_3 \ar[r, "f_{3,4}"'] & X_4
  \end{tikzcd}
\]
that is a $J$-cover (in the sense that the pair $\{f_{2,4}, f_{3,4}\} : X_2 \sqcup X_3 \to X_4$ is a covering family for $J$, and the pullback to $X_1$ is the obvious one). Mathlib's $\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.MayerVietorisSquare}$ (file \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/MayerVietorisSquare.lean}) bundles this datum together with its sheaf-theoretic exactness properties; we use it as a black box.

For us, the canonical example is a 2-affine open cover $X_4 = U_2 \cup U_3$ of an open $X_4 \subseteq C.\mathrm{left}.\mathrm{toTopCat}$ on a curve $C$, with $U_1 = U_2 \cap U_3$. After iter-017 + iter-018 + iter-019 land the LES theorem, this specialisation will be the engine of the Path-2 Serre-finiteness argument (`iter-020+`).

\subsection{First LES building block: the sum of two restriction maps}

\begin{definition}[Sum of two restriction maps in MV cohomology, $\HModulePrime$ flavor (iter-017)]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_toBiprod}
  \leanok
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category with $J : \mathrm{GrothendieckTopology}\,C$, and assume $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\mathrm{Type}\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $\HasExt(\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$. Let $S : J.\MayerVietorisSquare$, $F : \Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $n : \mathbb N$. Define
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\toBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n \;\colon\;
    (\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_4)
    \longrightarrow
    (\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_2)
    \boxplus
    (\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_3)
  \]
  by
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\toBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n \;:=\;
      \mathrm{biprod.lift}\bigl((\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{map}\,S.f_{2,4}.\mathtt{op},\;\;(\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{map}\,S.f_{3,4}.\mathtt{op}\bigr).
  \]
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \leanok
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf}
  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.MayerVietorisSquare.toBiprod}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L43--46) with $F.\cohomologyPresheaf \rightarrow \HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F$. The biproduct $\boxplus$ is the standard biproduct in $\AddCommGrpCat$ (Mathlib `Mathlib/Algebra/Category/Grp/Biproducts.lean`); it is well-defined because $\AddCommGrpCat$ has finite biproducts.
  Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-017) confirms the body typechecks end-to-end against current Mathlib + post-iter-016 project state, kernel-only axioms (\lstinline{propext}, \lstinline{Classical.choice}, \lstinline{Quot.sound}). The closure body is the one-line term \lstinline{biprod.lift ((HModule'_cohomologyPresheaf k F n).map S.f₂₄.op) ((HModule'_cohomologyPresheaf k F n).map S.f₃₄.op)}.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Second LES building block: the difference of two restriction maps}

\begin{definition}[Difference of two restriction maps in MV cohomology, $\HModulePrime$ flavor (iter-017)]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_fromBiprod}
  \leanok
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf}
  In the setting of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod}, define
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n \;\colon\;
    (\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_2)
    \boxplus
    (\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_3)
    \longrightarrow
    (\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_1)
  \]
  by
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n \;:=\;
      \mathrm{biprod.desc}\bigl((\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{map}\,S.f_{1,2}.\mathtt{op},\;\;-(\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{map}\,S.f_{1,3}.\mathtt{op}\bigr).
  \]
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \leanok
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf}
  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.MayerVietorisSquare.fromBiprod}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L67--70) with $F.\cohomologyPresheaf \rightarrow \HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F$. The negation $-(\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{map}\,S.f_{1,3}.\mathtt{op}$ is the additive inverse in the additive structure of $\AddCommGrpCat$-morphisms (the codomain category is $\AddCommGrpCat$ which is preadditive, so morphisms have additive inverses); the sign is the standard convention from the Mayer-Vietoris LES, encoding the alternating-sum structure of the Čech complex.
  Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-017) confirms the body typechecks end-to-end against current Mathlib + post-iter-016 project state, kernel-only axioms. The closure body is the one-line term \lstinline{biprod.desc ((HModule'_cohomologyPresheaf k F n).map S.f₁₂.op) (-(HModule'_cohomologyPresheaf k F n).map S.f₁₃.op)}.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Why these are the iter-017 targets]
  The Mayer-Vietoris LES theorem (Mathlib \texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L120--141) constructs a six-term sequence
  \[
    \cdots \longrightarrow H^n(S.X_4, F) \xrightarrow{\;\toBiprod\;} H^n(S.X_2, F) \boxplus H^n(S.X_3, F) \xrightarrow{\;\fromBiprod\;} H^n(S.X_1, F) \xrightarrow{\;\delta\;} H^{n+1}(S.X_4, F) \longrightarrow \cdots
  \]
  whose three building blocks are $\toBiprod$, $\fromBiprod$, and the connecting hom $\delta$. The first two are direct one-line term-mode \texttt{biprod.lift} / \texttt{biprod.desc} bodies on the cohomology presheaf's restriction maps; iter-017 lands them. Iter-018 proves the composition-is-zero lemma $\toBiprod \circ \fromBiprod = 0$ (Mathlib L72--75) — the verbatim Mathlib \lstinline{simp only} proof transfers cleanly because every rewrite step is value-category-agnostic (see Section~\ref{sec:hmodule_prime_mayer_vietoris_compose_zero}). The connecting hom $\delta$ requires the extension class machinery \lstinline{Ext.precomp} (Mathlib \texttt{Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/DerivedCategory/Ext/ExactSequences.lean}) applied to the Mayer-Vietoris square's induced short exact sequence; iter-019+ will scope it because Mathlib's \lstinline{MayerVietorisSquare.shortComplex_shortExact} (Mathlib \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/MayerVietorisSquare.lean} L240--268) is built from \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat.free}-yoneda — the $\ModuleCat\,k$ flavour requires a parallel construction with \lstinline{ModuleCat.free k}-yoneda, which is substantive multi-iteration work. Iter-019/020+ then lands the LES sequence itself, the iso to $\Ext.\mathrm{contravariantSequence}$ (Mathlib L120--141), and the exactness theorem.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Compatibility with Mathlib's $\AddCommGrpCat$-flavored LES]
  By construction, the codomain $\AddCommGrpCat$ of $\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf$ matches Mathlib's $F.\cohomologyPresheaf$ codomain (forced by $\Abelian.\extFunctor\,n$ always landing in $\AddCommGrpCat$). The biproduct $\boxplus$ in $\AddCommGrpCat$, the morphism additive structure, and the negation are all the same in both worlds. The only difference is the source of the cohomology presheaf: $F : \Sheaf\,J\,\AddCommGrpCat$ in Mathlib vs.\ $F : \Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$ in our setup. In particular, every Mathlib-level proof on $\toBiprod$ / $\fromBiprod$ (e.g.\ the composition-is-zero lemma at L72--75) transports verbatim to our setting once we replace `F.cohomologyPresheaf` with `HModule'_cohomologyPresheaf k F`; iter-018 uses this directly (Section~\ref{sec:hmodule_prime_mayer_vietoris_compose_zero}).
\end{remark}

\section{Mayer-Vietoris LES building block: composition-is-zero (iter-018)}
\label{sec:hmodule_prime_mayer_vietoris_compose_zero}

After Definitions~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod}--\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod} the two MV-LES building blocks $\toBiprod$ and $\fromBiprod$ are in scope. Iter-018 proves the third LES building block — the composition-is-zero relation $\toBiprod \circ \fromBiprod = 0$, which is one of the two zero-composition lemmas underpinning the eventual exactness theorem (the other being $\delta \circ \toBiprod = 0$, queued iter-019+).

\begin{lemma}[Composition $\toBiprod \circ \fromBiprod$ vanishes (iter-018)]
  \label{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod_fromBiprod}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_toBiprod_fromBiprod}
  \leanok
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod}
  In the setting of Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod}, the composition
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\toBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n \;\circ\; \HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n
    \;=\; 0
  \]
  in the morphism set $(\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_4) \to (\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{obj}\,(\mathrm{op}\,S.X_1)$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  \leanok
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod}
  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.MayerVietorisSquare.toBiprod\_fromBiprod}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L72--75). The proof reads as the composition of seven verbatim rewrites in a single \lstinline{simp only} block:
  \begin{enumerate}
    \item \lstinline{[HModule'_toBiprod, HModule'_fromBiprod]}: unfold the two iter-017 LES building blocks to expose the \lstinline{biprod.lift} / \lstinline{biprod.desc} shape.
    \item \lstinline{[biprod.lift_desc]}: apply the biproduct universal property
      \[ \mathrm{biprod.lift}\,a\,b \;\circ\; \mathrm{biprod.desc}\,c\,d \;=\; (a \circ c) + (b \circ d). \]
    \item \lstinline{[Preadditive.comp_neg]}: push the negation in $\fromBiprod$'s second argument through the composition.
    \item \lstinline{[← sub_eq_add_neg]}: rewrite the resulting $a + (-b)$ as $a - b$.
    \item \lstinline{[sub_eq_zero]}: reduce $a - b = 0$ to $a = b$ in the ambient \lstinline{AddCommGroup}.
    \item \lstinline{[← Functor.map_comp, ← op_comp]}: fuse the two consecutive applications of $(\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n).\mathrm{map}$ via contravariant functoriality (the $\mathrm{op}$ direction makes the morphism order swap).
    \item \lstinline{[S.toSquare.fac]}: close by the Mayer-Vietoris square's pullback-square factorisation $S.f_{1,2} \circ S.f_{2,4} = S.f_{1,3} \circ S.f_{3,4}$.
  \end{enumerate}
  Every rewrite step is independent of the value category: \lstinline{biprod.lift_desc} holds in any preadditive category with biproducts; \lstinline{Preadditive.comp_neg} holds in any preadditive category; \lstinline{sub_eq_add_neg}/\lstinline{sub_eq_zero} are elementary $\AddCommGroup$ arithmetic; \lstinline{Functor.map_comp}/\lstinline{op_comp} are categorical functoriality on $\Cop$; \lstinline{S.toSquare.fac} is independent of the value category entirely. Hence the proof transfers verbatim from $\Sheaf\,J\,\AddCommGrpCat$ to $\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$ with no modification.

